constDTO Data Type

This type contains constant information for the server. This information is useful in translating names that the user sees to IDs that other REST API endpoints accept. For example, the IncidentDTO has a property called "crimestatus_id". The valid values are stored in ConstDTO's "crime_statuses" property.

This information generally only changes for new releases of Resilient.

Namespace
(Default)
Properties
name data type type namespace min/max occurs description
action_object_types (custom) element 0/1 The supported action object type IDs and their names. The key portion of the map is the ID. The value portion is the display value.
action_types (custom) element 0/1 The supported action type IDs and their names. The key portion of the map is the ID. The value portion is the display value.
actions_framework actionsFrameworkInfoDTO element 0/1 Information about the actions framework.
artifact_types incidentArtifactTypeDTO element 0/unbounded A list of possible built-in artifact types. See incidentArtifactTypeDTO.
NOTE: Starting with version 28 this returns only the standard built-in system artifact types. This will be deprecated in version 29.
Using this data structure the incidentArtifactTypeDTO has only the following fields filled in:
id
name
desc
reg_exp
multi_aware
file
Instead of this use ORGRest GET to get the entire list of artifact types from fullOrgDTO.incident_artifact_types to get the full list of artifacts, both system and custom.
For create, update, delete operations on artifact types use OrgIncidentArtifactTypeREST resource.
crime_statuses (custom) element 0/1 A map of possible crime status values. The key portion of the map contains the ID of the crime status. The value portion contains a crimeStatusDTO.

See also: incidentDTO (crimestatus_id property)
data_formats (custom) element 0/1

A map of possible data formats. The following are examples of data formats:

  • Paper
  • Electronic
  • Verbal

The key portion of the map is the data format ID. The value contains a dataFormatTypeDTO.

See also: incidentPIIDTO (data_format property).
data_types (custom) element 0/1 A map of possible data type values. The key portion of the map contains the data type ID and the value portion contains a dataTypeDTO.

See also: fullIncidentDataDTO (dtm property)
geos (custom) element 0/1 A map of possible "geo" values. A geo is short for geographical region. It can be a region (such as Europe), country (such as United States) or a state/province (such as Massachusetts or Manitoba). The ID portion of the map is the geo ID. The value portion is a geoDTO.

Geo IDs are specified in the incidentCountsDTO to indicate how many records have been lost for a particular state/province.

Geo IDs are also used to specify the state and country properties of the incidentDTO.
harm_statuses (custom) element 0/1 A map of possible harm status values. The key portion of the map contains the ID of the harm status. The value portion contains a harmStatusDTO

See also: incidentPIIDTO (harmstatus_id property)
incident_statuses (custom) element 0/1 A map of possible incident statuses. The key portion of the map contains the status code and the value portion is a incidentStatusDTO.

See also: partialIncidentDTO (plan_status property)
industries (custom) element 0/1 A map of possible industry values. The key portion of the map contains the ID of the industry. The value portion contains an industryDTO.
industry_regulators_map (custom) element 0/1 A map of industries to regulators. These are regulators that apply for the specified industry. The key of this map is the industry ID and the value is the regulator ID. See also "regulators" and "industries" properties.
input_types (custom) element 0/1 A mapping of input type name to InputTypeDTO. This map allows you to get information about input types in the system (e.g. what "methods" they support for conditions and the valid types to which a type can be transformed).
max_artifacts int element 1/1 The maximum number of allowed artifacts to be loaded at same time.
max_attachment_mb int element 1/1 The maximum allowed attachment size (in megabytes).
message_destination_types (custom) element 0/1  
nist_attack_vectors (custom) element 0/1 A map of the possible NIST attack vector values. The key portion of the map contains the IDs and the value portion contains a NISTAttackVectorDTO.

These values come from NIST 800-61 (see http://csrc.nist.gov/publications/nistpubs/800-61rev2/SP800-61rev2.pdf).

See also: incidentDTO (nist_attack_vectors property)
period_types string element 0/unbounded An array of the possible period type values. These values are used when retrieving data from the OrgStatisticsREST resource (see the incidents_by_type_over_time and new_and_open_incidents endpoints).
pivot pivotConstDTO element 0/1 Get the constant data for pivoting services.

See PivotConstDTO.
predefined_items predefinedViewItemDTO element 0/unbounded An array of the default wizard items and incident tabs represented by PredefinedViewItemDTO elements.
regulators (custom) element 0/1 A map of possible regulator values. The key portion of the map contains the ID of the regulator. The value portion contains a regulatorDTO.

See also: regulatorsDTO.
script_languages (custom) element 0/1 The supported scripting languages.
server_version serverVersionDTO element 0/1 The server version.
states (custom) element 0/1 A map of possible US state values. The key portion of the map is the ID of the state The value portion of the map is a stateDTO.

Note that the ID for a given state is the same as it's geo ID. See the "geos" property.
task_statuses (custom) element 0/1 A map of possible task statuses. The key portion of the map is the task status code. The value portion is a taskStatusDTO.

See also: taskDTO (status property)
time_units timeUnitDTO element 0/unbounded A list of the supported time units for automatic tasks and system task overrides.
timeframes (custom) element 0/1 A map of possible timeframe values. The key portion of the map contains the IDs and the value portion contains a timeframeDTO.

  <actions_framework>

    <minor>...</minor>
